        {
          "h2": "Common Gmail workflows that outgrow Zapier",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The replacement candidate is usually a real inbox operation, not a vague email automation. One team is collecting invoice files, another is triaging a shared support mailbox, and another is preparing drafts from incoming customer messages. In each case, the operational question is the same: what exact Gmail event should count, and should the workflow react to a message, a thread conversation, a label change, a search match, or an attachment?",
            "Gmail makes that decision matter because message-level behavior, thread behavior, and label behavior are different. A workflow that should run once for the whole conversation can easily run on every reply instead. A workflow that should react to inbox conditions may be clearer with New Email Matching Search than with a later label event."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "Invoice and attachment intake",
              "paragraph": "Finance teams usually need one event per file, not one event per email. New Attachment triggers once per attachment on a received email, which is the safer pattern when each PDF, image, or statement has to be stored, parsed, and logged separately."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Shared inbox triage",
              "paragraph": "Operations teams often need to classify a Gmail message, apply labels, create a task, and sometimes open a draft. The workflow has to define whether replies belong to the same Gmail thread conversation process or whether each newly received message starts its own review."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Reply drafting and escalation",
              "paragraph": "When an incoming Gmail message feeds a draft or escalation path, the workflow should preserve message IDs, thread IDs, sender details, labels, and parsing results so a reviewer can confirm the action belongs to the right conversation."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "h2": "Where Gmail logic needs tighter operational scope",
          "paragraphs": [
            "A durable Gmail implementation starts with the right control surface. Some rules belong on messages, some on threads, some on labels, and some on searches. The workflow should state exactly which Gmail entity is authoritative and which IDs are stored for deduplication, replay, and audit.",
            "That matters because Gmail has specific constraints. Labels exist on messages, not on threads alone, and applying or removing a label on a thread affects all existing messages in that thread. New messages added to an already-labeled thread do not automatically inherit the prior thread label, so the workflow must decide whether to relabel, skip, or review those later replies."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "One run per conversation versus one run per message",
              "paragraph": "If the process should create one case for an entire conversation, use New Labeled Conversation when the business rule should fire only once for an entire thread. If each newly received Gmail message should be handled separately, deduplication needs to happen at the message level."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Label logic versus search logic",
              "paragraph": "Use New Email Matching Search when the inbox condition is best expressed as a Gmail query instead of a label or star state. That is often the cleaner choice when routing depends on sender, subject, inbox state, or other queryable message attributes."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Attachment-specific filtering",
              "paragraph": "New Labeled Email plus filter logic can silently fail if the Zap uses a legacy trigger or if the filter references thread-level fields instead of attachment-specific or message-specific fields. A direct implementation can validate exactly which fields are present before a downstream step runs."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "h2": "What to include in a Gmail replacement brief",
          "paragraphs": [
            "A useful brief reads like operating instructions for the mailbox. It should name the inbox, the Gmail labels in use, the searches in use, the kinds of messages that qualify, the systems that receive outputs, and the points where a human must approve parsing, routing, or drafts.",
            "It should also define ownership after launch. That includes logs, retry rules, exception queues, access controls, dashboards, and the process for changing labels, queries, reply templates, or attachment rules without breaking the workflow."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "Inputs and edge cases to document",
              "paragraph": "Provide sample Gmail messages, examples of valid and invalid threads, the current Zap steps, attachment types, label names, draft templates, and cases where a reply should or should not count as a new event."
            },
            {
              "h3": "IDs and audit fields to preserve",
              "paragraph": "The implementation should retain Gmail message IDs, thread IDs, labels, attachment metadata, draft IDs where relevant, downstream object IDs, timestamps, and reviewer decisions so each message and conversation can be traced."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Handover requirements",
              "paragraph": "Ask for runbooks, field maps, query definitions, label rules, failure-handling notes, and a change procedure. The finished system should let your team see which Gmail message triggered the workflow, why it qualified, and what happened next."
            }
          ]
        }
