    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Slack workflows that commonly outgrow Zapier</h2>\n<p>Most replacement projects start with a communication workflow that was reasonable at first: a Slack public channel message triggers an alert, a mention opens a follow-up task, or a reaction sends work to another team. As more channels, more users, and more edge cases appear, the original setup becomes harder to trust.</p>\n<p>The trigger label alone does not tell you much. Reliability depends on whether the event is instant or polling, whether replies are separated from top-level posts, whether the app can access a Slack private channel or multi-DM message, and whether outbound posting runs into Slack limits.</p>\n<h3>Escalation monitoring in public channels</h3>\n<p>A support team may watch a public channel for urgent customer updates and notify managers elsewhere. If the trigger is broad, side conversations, bot posts, and non-incident chatter can all look like real escalation events.</p>\n<h3>Reaction-based routing</h3>\n<p>A specific emoji might mean approve, hand off, or escalate. Direct ownership lets the workflow validate who reacted, which message they reacted to, and whether that message belongs to the right channel and process before anything moves.</p>\n<h3>Thread continuation rules</h3>\n<p>When work is supposed to stay in a thread, the integration needs to compare ts and thread_ts so a reply does not accidentally create a new case or trigger duplicate follow-up posts.</p>\n<h2>What direct Slack control should include</h2>\n<p>A good replacement does not just recreate Zap steps. It defines event scope, access checks, posting controls, retry behavior, exception handling, and a clear record of what happened at each stage.</p>\n<p>The point is straightforward operational control. When something goes wrong, the team should be able to see which event arrived, which rule accepted or rejected it, which conversation was targeted, and whether Slack accepted the outbound message.</p>\n<h3>Event scope and message identity</h3>\n<p>Specify whether the workflow starts from a Slack public channel message, a mention triggered event, a reaction, or a thread reply. Store the relevant message identifiers so later actions still target the correct conversation.</p>\n<h3>Access and membership checks</h3>\n<p>The integration should verify scopes and membership before reading from or posting into private channels, restricted conversations, or multi-DMs. Access problems should surface as explicit exceptions rather than silent misses.</p>\n<h3>Posting, throttling, and retries</h3>\n<p>Slack documents rate limits per API method per workspace/app, and posting is generally limited to about 1 message per second per channel. The workflow should queue outbound sends, honor Retry-After, and avoid burst behavior that produces delayed or partial delivery.</p>\n<h2>Operational details that prevent false runs and silent misses</h2>\n<p>Many Slack failures are really context failures. A message looks similar to the one you wanted, but it came from the wrong channel, from a bot, or from a thread root that should never have counted.</p>\n<p>Delivery issues are often discovered late, after someone notices an expected message never appeared. That is why direct implementations need clear logs, replay rules, and visible exception states instead of assuming every trigger and post behaved normally.</p>\n<h3>Filtering noise before it spreads</h3>\n<p>Broad message triggers can create noisy downstream automations because any public-channel message may qualify, including internal chatter, bots, and thread roots. Good filtering starts with explicit channel, user, and thread rules.</p>\n<h3>Avoiding polling gaps</h3>\n<p>Zapier states Slack triggers use Slack APIs and that some are instant while others are polling; the trigger type is fixed per trigger and cannot be changed. Where missed events are unacceptable, the brief should call out replay or fallback behavior clearly.</p>\n<h3>Making posting failures obvious</h3>\n<p>If Slack rejects a post, delays it, or returns a 429, operators should be able to see the failed attempt, retry timing, and final outcome in one place instead of piecing together the incident from several systems.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the GetForked brief</h2>\n<p>The best brief describes the real communication workflow, not just the app names. State which Slack event starts the process, what counts as valid context, what should be ignored, which conversations are in scope, and what a failed run looks like.</p>\n<p>It also helps to separate low-risk alerts from high-trust workflows. If one internal reminder can stay in Zapier, leave it out of scope and focus on the paths where message accuracy, access, and control matter.</p>\n<h3>Valid and invalid event examples</h3>\n<p>Include sample Slack messages, reactions, mentions, and thread replies, along with channel names, user roles, and exclusions such as bots, thread roots, or off-topic chatter.</p>\n<h3>Delivery and exception rules</h3>\n<p>List where outbound posts should go, how quickly they need to arrive, what should happen on HTTP 429 or access failure, and who should be notified when delivery fails.</p>\n<h3>Handover after launch</h3>\n<p>Ask for workflow notes, environment details, configuration guidance, test cases, and a handover checklist so the internal team can maintain the Slack integration without depending on undocumented knowledge.</p>",
